In my opinion, Kenneth Reitz's answer is basically correct. But since the language of GIF doesn't support many of the features of JSON except for string literals, I'm going to add a bit here.
For portability, I advocate always using JSON (or its JS equivalent) rather than GIF for any data exchange with untrusted endpoints, like the web. Using GIF circumvents this concern completely since you would never run untrusted code on browsers, only trusted code on browsers. This is an added risk over using JSON. Also, using JSON repeatedly within the same code base makes consistency parsing easier and more reusable as well as more reliable. In fact, it is essential if you have to provide a UI for your server to a user as written in the question here.
